OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,307,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30602
SC,0002
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F306A1775909467
OL,3,CArtemis II crew return safely to Earth
OL,5,FCommander Reid Wiseman, pilot Victor
OL,6,FGlover, Christina Koch and Canada's
OL,7,FJeremy Hansen emerged from their
OL,8,Fbobbing capsule into the sunlight off
OL,9,Fthe coast of San Diego in the early
OL,10,Fhours of Friday night into Monday
OL,11,Fmorning.
OL,13,FMilitary helicopters hoisted the
OL,14,Fastronauts one by one from an
OL,15,Finflatable raft docked to the capsule,
OL,16,Fhauling them aboard for the short trip
OL,17,Fto the Navy's awaiting recovery ship,
OL,18,Fthe USS John P. Murtha.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G2/12
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,307,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30603
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F306A1775909467
OL,3,CArtemis II crew return safely to Earth
OL,5,F"These were the ambassadors from
OL,6,Fhumanity to the stars that we sent out
OL,7,Fthere right now, and I can't imagine a
OL,8,Fbetter crew," NASA Administrator Jared
OL,9,FIsaacman said from the recovery ship.
OL,11,FNASA's Mission Control erupted in
OL,12,Fcelebration, with hundreds pouring in
OL,13,Ffrom the back support rooms. "We did
OL,14,Fit," NASA's Lori Glaze rejoiced at a
OL,15,Fnews conference. "Welcome to our
OL,16,Fmoonshot."
OL,26,@mD@AOUpD@MO]uD@^OUvD@DO]wD@ROUxD@JO]
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G3/12
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,307,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30604
SC,0004
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F306A1775909467
OL,3,CArtemis II crew return safely to Earth
OL,5,FTheir Orion capsule, dubbed Integrity,
OL,6,Fmade the entire plunge on autopilot.
OL,7,FThe lunar cruiser hit the atmosphere
OL,8,Ftravelling at 33 times the speed of
OL,9,Fsound.
OL,11,FAs the capsule approached Earth, it
OL,12,Fbecame engulfed in red-hot plasma
OL,13,Fduring peak heating and entered a
OL,14,Fplanned communication blackout.
OL,16,FDuring this period, the capsule's life-
OL,17,Fprotecting heat shield had to
OL,18,Fwithstand around 10,000 degrees, twice
OL,19,Fthe temperature of the surface of the
OL,20,FSun.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G4/12
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,307,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30605
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F306A1775909467
OL,3,CArtemis II crew return safely to Earth
OL,5,FWatching the drama unfold nearly 2,000
OL,6,Fmiles (3,200 kilometres) away, the
OL,7,Fastronauts' families huddled in
OL,8,FMission Control's viewing room,
OL,9,Fcheering when the capsule emerged from
OL,10,Fits six-minute blackout and again at
OL,11,Fsplashdown.
OL,13,FThe last time NASA and the Defence
OL,14,FDepartment teamed up for a lunar
OL,15,Fcrew's reentry was Apollo 17 in 1972.
OL,17,FKoch became the first woman to fly to
OL,18,Fthe moon, Glover the first Black
OL,19,Fastronaut, and Hansen the first non-US
OL,20,Fcitizen.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G5/12
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,307,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30606
SC,0006
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F306A1775909467
OL,3,CArtemis II crew return safely to Earth
OL,5,FLaunched from Florida on April 1,
OL,6,FArtemis II didn't land on the moon or
OL,7,Feven orbit it. The trip instead broke
OL,8,FApollo 13's distance record and marked
OL,9,Fthe farthest that humans have ever
OL,10,Fjourneyed from Earth when the crew
OL,11,Freached 252,756 miles (406,771
OL,12,Fkilometres).
OL,14,FDuring Monday's record-breaking flyby,
OL,15,Fthey documented scenes of the moon's
OL,16,Ffar side never seen before by the
OL,17,Fhuman eye, along with a total solar
OL,18,Feclipse. The eclipse, in particular,
OL,19,F"just blew all of us away," Glover
OL,20,Fsaid.
OL,26,@{D@AOU{D@[O]
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G6/12
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
